WEBVTT

00:16.967 --> 00:19.066
♪ (CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

00:19.133 --> 00:20.500
JOHN WILSON: <i>Hey, New York.</i>

00:22.300 --> 00:24.300
<i>Life is filled</i>
<i>with precious moments.</i>

00:26.200 --> 00:29.567
<i>Ones, uh, that we wish</i>
<i>we could hang on to forever.</i>

00:33.400 --> 00:35.500
<i>But our ability</i>
<i>to recall everything,</i>

00:35.567 --> 00:37.667
<i>no matter</i>
<i>how much it means to us,</i>

00:37.734 --> 00:40.834
<i>gets worse and worse over time.</i>

00:40.900 --> 00:43.433
<i>And if you don't have</i>
<i>an accurate record,</i>

00:43.500 --> 00:45.300
<i>you may never be able to, uh,</i>

00:45.367 --> 00:47.700
<i>trust your own version</i>
<i>of events.</i>

00:49.066 --> 00:51.900
<i>And then you'll just end up</i>
<i>remembering things</i>

00:51.967 --> 00:54.000
<i>the way that someone else</i>
<i>wants you to...</i>

00:55.734 --> 00:57.667
<i>but it doesn't have</i>
<i>to be this way.</i>

00:58.600 --> 01:00.066
<i>So stick with me,</i>

01:00.133 --> 01:03.266
<i>and I'll show you</i>
<i>how to turn every waking moment</i>

01:03.333 --> 01:05.767
<i>into something</i>
<i>that's impossible to forget.</i>

01:08.500 --> 01:10.633
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

01:11.633 --> 01:13.233
<i>Now, a good memory is</i>

01:13.300 --> 01:15.867
<i>one of the most attractive</i>
<i>qualities a person can have.</i>

01:16.900 --> 01:18.734
<i>My memory's not very good,</i>

01:18.800 --> 01:22.433
<i>and it's always</i>
<i>made me feel insecure.</i>

01:22.500 --> 01:25.300
<i>This is kind of why I started</i>
<i>shooting so much video.</i>

01:26.600 --> 01:29.200
<i>I've also been writing down</i>
<i>every single thing I do</i>

01:29.266 --> 01:32.700
<i>every single day</i>
<i>for over a decade now.</i>

01:32.767 --> 01:35.233
<i>Whenever I do something</i>
<i>or go somewhere,</i>

01:35.300 --> 01:36.934
<i>I put it right here</i>
<i>in these books.</i>

01:37.000 --> 01:38.767
♪ (CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

01:38.834 --> 01:41.367
<i>On January 10th, 2018,</i>

01:41.433 --> 01:45.233
<i>I woke up at 8 a.m.</i>
<i>and ate four strips of bacon.</i>

01:46.867 --> 01:49.734
<i>On August 22nd, 2014,</i>

01:49.800 --> 01:53.000
<i>I got a haircut</i>
<i>at, uh, Home Run Barbershop.</i>

01:53.066 --> 01:55.367
<i>And on March 12th</i>
<i>of the same year,</i>

01:55.433 --> 01:57.166
<i>uh, I got a salad for lunch</i>

01:57.233 --> 02:00.266
<i>and accidentally dropped it</i>
<i>all over 32nd Street.</i>

02:01.300 --> 02:03.166
<i>It's kind of like time</i>
<i>traveling.</i>

02:03.233 --> 02:05.133
<i>If I ever need</i>
<i>to remember something,</i>

02:05.200 --> 02:07.734
<i>I can just go back to my book</i>
<i>and read about that day,</i>

02:07.800 --> 02:09.433
<i>and I'm immediately transported.</i>

02:10.800 --> 02:13.934
<i>But unfortunately,</i>
<i>this isn't memory,</i>

02:14.033 --> 02:16.767
<i>because the second</i>
<i>I look away from these books,</i>

02:16.834 --> 02:19.266
<i>everything just begins</i>
<i>to blur together</i>

02:20.533 --> 02:24.834
<i>and I can barely remember</i>
<i>who I am or how I got there.</i>

02:25.967 --> 02:27.400
<i>And if I'm not careful,</i>

02:27.467 --> 02:31.033
<i>one day all these records</i>
<i>could just go up in smoke.</i>

02:34.100 --> 02:36.967
<i>But New York</i>
<i>can be a painful place</i>

02:37.033 --> 02:39.100
<i>to have a good memory</i>

02:39.166 --> 02:41.600
<i>because the better</i>
<i>you remember it,</i>

02:41.667 --> 02:44.533
<i>the less, uh,</i>
<i>you recognize over time.</i>

02:46.200 --> 02:48.700
<i>There used to be a-- a bar</i>
<i>on 2nd Avenue, uh,</i>

02:48.767 --> 02:51.400
<i>called Mars Bar</i>
<i>that I used to go to.</i>

02:51.467 --> 02:54.433
<i>But now it's a TD Bank.</i>

02:55.533 --> 02:57.700
<i>Um, thankfully, it looks like</i>

02:57.767 --> 03:01.500
<i>some of the regulars, uh,</i>
<i>still hang out there, though.</i>

03:03.233 --> 03:05.166
<i>They also recently demolished</i>

03:05.233 --> 03:08.800
<i>one of my favorite, uh,</i>
<i>movie theaters.</i>

03:08.867 --> 03:13.300
<i>There aren't many left</i>
<i>quite like it in New York City.</i>

03:13.367 --> 03:15.400
<i>But at least it, um, looked like</i>

03:15.467 --> 03:17.867
<i>they were having</i>
<i>a good time destroying it.</i>

03:20.633 --> 03:22.367
<i>A friend told me recently about</i>

03:22.433 --> 03:24.000
<i>someone who lives</i>
<i>in my neighborhood</i>

03:24.066 --> 03:25.333
<i>who has such a good memory</i>

03:25.400 --> 03:28.367
<i>that she actually competes</i>
<i>in memory competitions.</i>

03:28.433 --> 03:31.000
<i>And she let me come over</i>
<i>to look at some of her awards.</i>

03:31.066 --> 03:32.200
JOHN: Let me see this--

03:32.266 --> 03:34.900
-YANJAA WINTERSOUL: Oops-- Yeah.
-JOHN: Oh my god, sorry.

03:34.967 --> 03:38.934
Yes, this is... yeah,
World Memory Championship 2017.

03:39.467 --> 03:42.200
These are Singapore,

03:42.266 --> 03:45.066
and then there are some from,
I guess, Sweden, Fra--

03:45.133 --> 03:47.700
not France, what is this?

03:47.767 --> 03:50.633
JOHN: <i>She seemed a little bored,</i>
<i>but maybe that's because</i>

03:50.700 --> 03:53.734
<i>this was her third interview</i>
<i>in 24 hours.</i>

03:54.567 --> 03:55.700
Were there any methods of yours

03:55.767 --> 03:57.800
that you used
to improve your memory?

03:57.867 --> 04:00.433
Uh, most competitors
use a technique called

04:00.500 --> 04:02.200
the memory palace technique.

04:02.266 --> 04:03.567
For example, if you want to know

04:03.633 --> 04:05.900
the periodic table
of elements in order,

04:05.967 --> 04:08.300
then you can place them
in the memory palace

04:08.367 --> 04:12.667
and go, like, "H, hydrogen,"
so maybe on your bed

04:12.734 --> 04:15.133
you put... like, lots of water.

04:15.200 --> 04:16.967
Your bed is suddenly
just made of water,

04:17.033 --> 04:20.100
and then your nightstand
might be made out of balloons

04:20.166 --> 04:22.133
so then you remember
helium balloons.

04:22.200 --> 04:25.500
I mean, you kind of just
move along in a logical pattern.

04:25.567 --> 04:29.033
JOHN: <i>The technique</i>
<i>she told me about</i>
<i>sounded like a good idea.</i>

04:29.100 --> 04:31.066
<i>All you have to do</i>
<i>is close your eyes</i>

04:31.133 --> 04:33.467
<i>and imagine you're walking</i>
<i>through a physical space</i>

04:33.533 --> 04:34.800
<i>that you know really well...</i>

04:34.867 --> 04:36.767
♪ (MYSTERIOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

04:36.834 --> 04:39.734
<i>...and mentally place the things</i>
<i>you want to remember,</i>

04:39.800 --> 04:41.834
<i>uh, all along your path.</i>

04:44.500 --> 04:46.133
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

04:46.200 --> 04:47.934
JOHN: <i>So I tried to use it</i>
<i>to remember</i>

04:48.000 --> 04:50.033
<i>my, uh, grocery store list.</i>

04:50.100 --> 04:55.133
<i>And I'll use my commute to work</i>
<i>as, uh, the memory palace thing.</i>

04:55.200 --> 04:57.900
<i>So, here's what it looks like</i>
<i>in my head.</i>

