<i>but I finally spotted</i>
<i>an employee</i>

07:02.867 --> 07:04.633
<i>uh, who didn't seem too busy.</i>

07:04.700 --> 07:06.500
-CHRIS ANATRA: What's that?
-JOHN: A Zagnut bar?

07:06.567 --> 07:07.667
No.

07:07.734 --> 07:09.433
JOHN: Uh, it's like a candy bar.

07:10.734 --> 07:11.667
Okay.

07:11.734 --> 07:12.834
JOHN: <i>It turned out, uh,</i>

07:12.900 --> 07:14.967
<i>he didn't actually</i>
<i>work at Stop & Shop,</i>

07:15.033 --> 07:18.500
<i>but he was the creator</i>
<i>of the inventory software</i>

07:18.567 --> 07:21.000
<i>used to organize everything.</i>

07:21.066 --> 07:23.500
CHRIS: Pretty much,
from A to Z, all of their needs,

07:23.567 --> 07:25.200
anything
that needs traceability,

07:25.266 --> 07:27.433
is what our software
is really good at.

07:27.500 --> 07:30.533
JOHN: <i>I told him I was making</i>
<i>a student film about memory,</i>

07:30.600 --> 07:33.600
<i>and he started sharing</i>
<i>some of the weird experiences</i>

07:33.667 --> 07:37.567
<i>he's had in the world</i>
<i>of supermarket inventory.</i>

07:38.633 --> 07:39.867
I specifically remember

07:39.934 --> 07:42.967
this being called
Stouffer's Stovetop Stuffing.

07:43.033 --> 07:45.934
But it's always been, now,
Kraft Stovetop Stuffing.

07:46.000 --> 07:47.900
And it's always been that way,
it wasn't--

07:48.000 --> 07:50.900
From the 1970s,
it's always been Kraft.

07:50.967 --> 07:52.367
But I remember the commercials,

07:52.433 --> 07:54.066
I remember everything
about being it

07:54.133 --> 07:56.400
called Stouffer's
Stovetop Stuffing.

07:56.467 --> 07:59.667
So, here's another one, too.
The Raisin Bran guy?

07:59.734 --> 08:02.233
I know he always
used to have sunglasses,

08:02.300 --> 08:05.066
but now, he's never
wore sunglasses, ever.

08:06.033 --> 08:09.100
Febreze, I always remember
it being spelled

08:09.166 --> 08:11.066
with two e's, "Febreeze."

08:11.133 --> 08:12.834
Now it's "Feb-rez."

08:12.900 --> 08:15.667
And it's always been this way.
Like, that's the point...

08:15.734 --> 08:17.800
that I want to make.
It's always spelled this way,

08:17.867 --> 08:20.200
it's never been spelled
with the two <i>e's.</i>

08:20.266 --> 08:22.867
JOHN: <i>Not everything</i>
<i>he said resonated with me,</i>

08:22.934 --> 08:27.266
<i>but I definitely thought, uh,</i>
<i>"Febreze" had more e's in it.</i>

08:27.333 --> 08:30.066
<i>So, when he invited me</i>
<i>back to his, uh, office</i>

08:30.133 --> 08:32.266
<i>to check out</i>
<i>his inventory software,</i>

08:32.333 --> 08:35.100
<i>I said, uh, "Yes, sir."</i>

08:35.166 --> 08:37.500
There's no...
there's no Stovetop Stuffing

08:37.567 --> 08:40.500
-for Stouffer's in...
-CHRIS: No stuffing.

08:40.567 --> 08:42.800
However, I'm gonna bring one up

08:42.867 --> 08:44.233
that myself and my dad

08:44.300 --> 08:47.066
got into, like,
a little kerfuffle about.

08:47.133 --> 08:50.800
Um, it was about
the JFK assassination.

08:50.867 --> 08:52.700
Like, if you look at
the picture of the car here,

08:52.767 --> 08:54.233
there's, like...

08:54.300 --> 08:56.300
all these extra people
in the car.

08:56.367 --> 08:58.500
I-- I always remember
there distinctly being

08:58.567 --> 09:00.200
four people in the car,

09:00.266 --> 09:03.133
and then as I was searching
to try to find an answer,

09:03.200 --> 09:06.300
because every video
was the same Zapruder film,

09:06.367 --> 09:09.567
I saw, "JFK assassination
Mandela effect."

09:09.633 --> 09:11.934
I'm like, "Mandela effect?

09:12.000 --> 09:13.567
What the heck
is a Mandela effect?"

09:13.633 --> 09:15.166
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

09:15.233 --> 09:17.967
Some people
have a very distinct memory

09:18.033 --> 09:22.800
that Nelson Mandela was killed
in prison in the late 1980s,

09:22.867 --> 09:26.533
and then, I think around 2009,
were kind of shocked to find out

09:26.600 --> 09:29.066
that Nelson Mandela
was still alive.

09:29.133 --> 09:34.033
So that was the first recorded
group remembering of an event

09:34.100 --> 09:36.433
that did not match
the historical record.

09:36.500 --> 09:38.166
JOHN: Oh, okay.

09:38.233 --> 09:40.967
So, is-- is there, like...

09:42.133 --> 09:43.166
What, uh...

09:43.233 --> 09:44.433
The more you look into it,

09:44.500 --> 09:46.233
the more you see
these different things,

09:46.300 --> 09:51.533
not just in food service,
but in geography of the planet.

09:51.600 --> 09:55.834
For example,
I remember when South America

09:55.900 --> 09:57.734
used to be under North America,

09:57.800 --> 10:00.133
not pushed all the way out
towards Africa.

10:00.200 --> 10:03.500
Or your heart used to be
offset to the left.

10:03.567 --> 10:06.066
Now, it's just about
in the center of your chest.

10:06.133 --> 10:08.133
From what I remember,
it used to be <i>Sex in the City,</i>

10:08.200 --> 10:09.967
and now it's <i>Sex and the City.</i>

10:10.033 --> 10:14.600
Is the word "a lot" one word,
a-l-o-t, or is it two words?

10:14.667 --> 10:18.533
"Sometimes," is it s-o-m-e--
Is it two different words, or--

10:18.600 --> 10:20.533
I actually called
the Scotchgard company,

10:20.600 --> 10:22.900
and I'm like, "When did you guys
change your product name

10:22.967 --> 10:26.266
from 'guard,' g-u-a-r-d,
to g-a-r-d?"

10:26.333 --> 10:30.033
"Objects in mirror
are closer than they appear."

10:31.467 --> 10:33.066
Is there a hidden meaning?

10:33.133 --> 10:35.333
Are we being communicated with

10:35.400 --> 10:38.400
somehow regarding
these Mandela effects?

10:38.467 --> 10:40.700
Is it trying-- Are we trying
to be taught something

10:40.767 --> 10:43.066
that we haven't quite
grasped yet?

10:43.133 --> 10:46.133
So, myself and others are,
like, really looking into that,

10:46.200 --> 10:48.467
and we're starting
to find patterns.

10:48.533 --> 10:50.533
JOHN: <i>I still didn't have</i>
<i>all my groceries,</i>

10:50.600 --> 10:53.500
<i>but I was hypnotized</i>
<i>by his elaborate theories.</i>

10:53.567 --> 10:55.834
JOHN: Were you afraid of Y2K
when it was about to happen?

10:55.900 --> 10:58.066
No, actually, I really wasn't.

10:58.133 --> 10:59.500
JOHN: <i>And I soon learned that</i>

10:59.567 --> 11:01.867
<i>this was more</i>
<i>than just a hobby for him.</i>

11:01.934 --> 11:03.600
The first official

11:03.667 --> 11:06.400
Mandela Effect Conference
is being organized,

11:06.467 --> 11:10.066
so that people can feel
at ease about their memory,

11:10.133 --> 11:12.300
in that, "Don't worry,
there's a lot of people

11:12.367 --> 11:14.734
that have the same type
of memories that you have,

11:14.800 --> 11:16.333
and they're--
and they're shared."

11:16.400 --> 11:18.066
So there's gonna be
a group of people

11:18.133 --> 11:19.633
coming together
to talk about that.

11:19.700 --> 11:22.033
I think it's gonna be
an-- an historic event.

11:22.100 --> 11:24.200
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES♪

11:24.266 --> 11:27.467
JOHN: <i>After I left,</i>
<i>I couldn't stop noticing, uh,</i>

