<i>But there was definitely</i>
<i>something going on.</i>

12:00.900 --> 12:02.900
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

12:02.967 --> 12:04.967
<i>I walked outside</i>
<i>of my apartment recently,</i>

12:05.033 --> 12:08.700
<i>and I noticed that the city</i>
<i>changed out all the garbage cans</i>

12:08.767 --> 12:12.166
<i>to the older, uh,</i>
<i>"Oscar the Grouch" style,</i>

12:12.233 --> 12:14.734
<i>uh, which I thought was weird.</i>

12:14.800 --> 12:18.333
<i>As I kept walking, my neighbors</i>
<i>looked different, too.</i>

12:19.800 --> 12:21.834
<i>I was--</i>
<i>I was getting really confused,</i>

12:21.900 --> 12:23.734
<i>but I soon realized</i>

12:23.800 --> 12:27.633
<i>I had actually just stumbled</i>
<i>onto the set of a movie.</i>

12:27.700 --> 12:31.333
<i>It was Stephen Spielberg's</i>
<i>remake of</i> <i>West Side Story.</i>

12:31.400 --> 12:33.300
<i>And they were pretending</i>
<i>that Queens</i>

12:33.367 --> 12:36.133
<i>was the Upper West Side</i>
<i>in the early '40s.</i>

12:37.567 --> 12:39.066
<i>For the rest of the week,</i>

12:39.133 --> 12:42.166
<i>it was hard to tell who was</i>
<i>a human and who was an actor.</i>

12:43.200 --> 12:45.700
<i>And I kept getting in trouble</i>
<i>walking around</i>

12:45.767 --> 12:47.533
<i>because I was</i>
<i>from the wrong era.</i>

12:49.367 --> 12:50.467
<i>A week later,</i>

12:50.533 --> 12:53.200
<i>I thought my neighborhood</i>
<i>was back to normal,</i>

12:53.266 --> 12:56.834
<i>but it turned out they were, uh,</i>
<i>just shooting another movie.</i>

12:58.367 --> 13:02.000
<i>After that, I had trouble</i>
<i>trusting anything I saw.</i>

13:02.066 --> 13:05.400
<i>And I just started assuming</i>
<i>that everything was a movie.</i>

13:06.734 --> 13:08.200
<i>This looks like a good one.</i>

13:09.066 --> 13:10.767
<i>Excited for this one</i>
<i>to come out.</i>

13:11.467 --> 13:13.033
<i>But the more I paid attention,</i>

13:13.100 --> 13:16.367
<i>the more I wondered if some</i>
<i>of this confusion was by design.</i>

13:16.433 --> 13:17.667
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

13:17.734 --> 13:19.667
<i>I was walking</i>
<i>by the Thanksgiving Day parade,</i>

13:19.734 --> 13:21.600
<i>and I saw that</i>
<i>there was a malfunction</i>

13:21.667 --> 13:23.800
<i>with</i>
<i>the Ronald McDonald balloon,</i>

13:23.867 --> 13:27.367
<i>and it had to be pulled</i>
<i>in the middle of the event.</i>

13:27.433 --> 13:29.567
<i>But later, when I mentioned this</i>
<i>to a friend</i>

13:29.633 --> 13:31.700
<i>who had watched</i>
<i>the parade on TV,</i>

13:31.767 --> 13:34.567
<i>they had no idea</i>
<i>what I was talking about.</i>

13:34.633 --> 13:36.233
<i>It turned out,</i>
<i>the live broadcast</i>

13:36.300 --> 13:38.567
<i>had spliced in footage</i>
<i>from last year's float</i>

13:38.633 --> 13:40.333
<i>to make it seem</i>
<i>to viewers at home</i>

13:40.400 --> 13:42.066
<i>that everything was normal,</i>

13:42.133 --> 13:44.900
<i>while in reality,</i>
<i>Ronald's deflating carcass</i>

13:44.967 --> 13:48.066
<i>was being pulverized</i>
<i>in the middle of 42nd Street</i>

13:48.133 --> 13:50.834
<i>while spectators</i>
<i>watched in horror.</i>

13:52.500 --> 13:55.500
<i>This act of deception</i>
<i>created two groups of people</i>

13:55.567 --> 13:58.834
<i>with completely different</i>
<i>memories of the same event,</i>

13:59.667 --> 14:01.333
<i>and neither of them is wrong.</i>

14:03.600 --> 14:06.433
<i>The conference that the guy</i>
<i>mentioned was happening soon.</i>

14:06.500 --> 14:09.734
<i>And I was starting to feel</i>
<i>like I shouldn't miss it.</i>

14:09.800 --> 14:13.633
<i>So I caught a cheap flight</i>
<i>to, uh, Ketchum, Idaho,</i>

14:13.700 --> 14:16.734
<i>where the first-ever</i>
<i>Mandela Effect Conference</i>

14:16.800 --> 14:22.066
<i>was being held</i>
<i>at a Best Western, uh, "Plus"</i>

14:22.133 --> 14:24.800
<i>in the, uh, Pow Wow Room.</i>

14:24.867 --> 14:27.934
<i>The conference organizers</i>
<i>were just getting set up.</i>

14:28.033 --> 14:31.867
<i>But once they installed</i>
<i>their, uh, custom sign</i>

14:31.934 --> 14:33.834
<i>that they had shipped in,</i>

14:33.900 --> 14:37.734
<i>uh, the host took a moment</i>
<i>to chat with me.</i>

14:37.800 --> 14:40.633
So, in my head, it's always been
"Berenstein" Bears.

14:40.700 --> 14:42.567
I learned to read
on those books.

14:42.633 --> 14:46.033
I was as sure as my next breath
that it was an <i>e.</i>

14:47.467 --> 14:48.967
Turns out
it's never been an <i>e,</i>

14:49.033 --> 14:50.667
it's always been an <i>a.</i>

14:50.734 --> 14:52.633
And that bothers me a lot.

14:52.700 --> 14:55.000
That was my first one
I ever found.

14:55.734 --> 14:57.867
And I couldn't let it go.

14:57.934 --> 15:01.800
When you know what you know,
you can't deny your memory.

15:01.867 --> 15:03.400
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

15:03.467 --> 15:05.066
JOHN:
<i>Everyone started to file in</i>

15:05.133 --> 15:07.867
<i>and sample free veggies and dip.</i>

15:08.934 --> 15:11.333
<i>The guy from the supermarket</i>
<i>showed up, too.</i>

15:12.400 --> 15:14.133
<i>There was a lot</i>
<i>of literature there.</i>

15:14.200 --> 15:17.934
<i>And, uh,</i>
<i>custom apparel and decals.</i>

15:19.033 --> 15:21.266
<i>People were having</i>
<i>very animated discussions</i>

15:21.333 --> 15:22.800
<i>about their different theories.</i>

15:22.867 --> 15:24.100
Like, I was just hearing that

15:24.166 --> 15:26.467
-somebody remembered
having a dog...
-Right.

15:26.533 --> 15:28.934
...and then their mother's like,
"No, we never had a dog,

15:29.000 --> 15:31.233
-we were a cat family. Never."
-Right, right.

15:31.300 --> 15:33.600
And she has all these memories
of this dog.

15:33.667 --> 15:34.800
You know,
where did they come from?

15:34.867 --> 15:36.433
-This happens a lot?
-Yeah.

15:36.500 --> 15:37.867
JOHN:
<i>All the presenters talked about</i>

15:37.934 --> 15:40.567
<i>some of the most</i>
<i>well-known, uh, Mandela effects.</i>

15:41.800 --> 15:43.800
<i>Minds were being</i>
<i>absolutely obliterated</i>

15:43.867 --> 15:46.567
<i>with all of this</i>
<i>forbidden knowledge.</i>

15:46.633 --> 15:48.834
Now, when you look
at this picture,
do you see a Mandela effect?

15:48.900 --> 15:51.100
-AUDIENCE MEMBER 1: Yes. Yes.
-AUDIENCE MEMBER 2:
Yeah. The stripes.

15:51.166 --> 15:53.633
The stripes!
Those were never there before.

15:53.700 --> 15:55.166
Not-- not that I remember.

15:56.100 --> 15:58.266
JOHN: <i>But the more</i>
<i>I talked with people,</i>

15:58.333 --> 16:01.100
<i>uh, the more I realized that</i>
<i>they didn't think of this</i>

16:01.166 --> 16:03.567
<i>as a memory problem at all.</i>

16:03.633 --> 16:05.567
What do I think
the Mandela effect is?

16:06.433 --> 16:10.233
Um, I would say
it's a timeline shift,

16:10.300 --> 16:13.233
you know, um,
proof of the multiverse...

16:14.033 --> 16:16.734
you know, different timelines.

16:16.800 --> 16:21.533
It's like evidential existence
of parallel timelines.

16:22.233 --> 16:23.467
JOHN: <i>Everyone there,</i>

16:23.533 --> 16:26.100
<i>no matter</i>
<i>their individual experience,</i>

16:26.166 --> 16:27.800
<i>was on the same page about this.</i>

16:27.867 --> 16:29.233
So, the Mandela effect

16:29.300 --> 16:32.633
is the consequence
of jumping timelines

16:32.700 --> 16:37.734
while holding memories
of the previous timeline.

16:37.800 --> 16:40.166
JOHN: <i>In their minds,</i>
<i>their memories were perfect,</i>

16:40.233 --> 16:43.200
<i>and they were the chosen few</i>
<i>who could remember details</i>

16:43.266 --> 16:46.967
<i>from alternate dimensions</i>
<i>that they once inhabited.</i>

16:47.033 --> 16:49.500
PRESENTER:
And I remember Benicio del Toro,

16:49.567 --> 16:51.600
he died around 2001.

16:51.667 --> 16:54.467
I think both of them are
still alive right now, I hope,

16:54.533 --> 16:56.033
and I'm not sure
what that's about,

16:56.100 --> 16:57.533
but it is interesting.

16:58.667 --> 17:00.600
JOHN: <i>They were using</i>
<i>the most complicated</i>

17:00.667 --> 17:04.166
<i>scientific theories possible</i>
<i>to explain what most people</i>

17:04.233 --> 17:07.200
<i>would consider, uh,</i>
<i>everyday forgetfulness.</i>

17:07.266 --> 17:09.533
Personally, I think--
I've-- I've done this.

17:09.600 --> 17:12.133
Literally, I'll have a pen
that I'd like to write with.

17:12.200 --> 17:15.300
I put it down, I stood up,
turned around,

17:15.367 --> 17:17.834
and went, "Oh, I want the pen,"
and it was gone.

17:17.900 --> 17:19.767
It was not there.

17:19.834 --> 17:21.400
And I just...
looked on the floor,

17:21.467 --> 17:23.166
looked on the table, nothing.

17:23.233 --> 17:26.100
Three days later,
I'm sitting at the computer

17:26.166 --> 17:27.567
like this with the pen,

17:27.633 --> 17:29.667
and I have no idea
where it came from.

17:30.900 --> 17:33.767
Um... no.

17:33.834 --> 17:35.567
JOHN: <i>I purchased his book</i>
<i>to learn more</i>

17:35.633 --> 17:38.433
<i>about his, uh,</i>
<i>quantum timeline theory,</i>

17:38.500 --> 17:40.433
<i>and I took it back to my room,</i>

17:40.500 --> 17:43.133
<i>which was conveniently</i>
<i>on the other side of the wall</i>

17:43.200 --> 17:44.800
<i>from the convention space.</i>

17:45.834 --> 17:48.300
<i>There wasn't a lot of,</i>
<i>uh, science in there,</i>

17:48.367 --> 17:50.400
<i>but in the first 30 pages,</i>

17:50.467 --> 17:53.000
<i>the author claims</i>
<i>to have invented Pokémon...</i>

17:53.066 --> 17:56.033
<i>and met Mark Twain in a hot tub.</i>

17:57.166 --> 17:58.500
<i>This didn't explain much,</i>

17:58.567 --> 18:01.000
<i>and I was hoping to get</i>
<i>more of an explanation</i>

18:01.066 --> 18:02.700
<i>when the Q&A began.</i>

18:12.767 --> 18:14.500
CHRIS: It's usually,
um, some kind of, like,

18:14.567 --> 18:16.700
um, hard drive technologies.

18:18.166 --> 18:19.834
CHRIS: What's that?

18:19.900 --> 18:21.867
-AUDIENCE MEMBER 3: Silicon.
-CHRIS: Yeah, I think ultimate--

18:21.934 --> 18:23.667
yeah, ultimately silicon.

18:24.633 --> 18:26.200
CHRIS: Yeah, yeah.

18:26.967 --> 18:28.233
AUDIENCE MEMBER 3:

18:32.333 --> 18:33.633
CHRIS: Okay.

18:37.500 --> 18:39.734
JOHN: <i>The conference</i>
<i>was almost over.</i>

18:39.800 --> 18:41.567
<i>Uh, but before leaving,</i>

18:41.633 --> 18:45.767
<i>I decided to spend some time</i>
<i>with the organizer, Jerry.</i>

18:45.834 --> 18:49.333
<i>He wanted to show me the town's,</i>
<i>uh, other Best Western,</i>

18:49.400 --> 18:51.567
<i>where he worked</i>
<i>as a night manager</i>

18:51.633 --> 18:53.967
<i>and, uh, actually</i>
<i>lived there too.</i>

18:54.033 --> 18:55.367
According to science,

18:55.433 --> 18:57.734
we're in the Orion Arm
of the Milky Way.

18:57.800 --> 18:59.633
Generally speaking,
the dash was always

18:59.700 --> 19:01.500
in the middle
on the Coca-Cola logo.

19:01.567 --> 19:05.166
The company Costco
lost their <i>t.</i>

19:05.233 --> 19:07.233
Another strange thing
about the flip-flops

19:07.300 --> 19:10.867
is all evidence of the flip
disappears after the flop.

19:10.934 --> 19:12.834
JOHN: So, are your coworkers
gonna be in there?

19:12.900 --> 19:14.300
JERRY:
They will be. They will be.

19:14.367 --> 19:16.800
And all of them
are affected, too.

19:16.867 --> 19:18.967
They were actually affected
before I ever got here.

19:19.033 --> 19:20.467
'Cause people asked them
the questions,

19:20.533 --> 19:22.633
and they realized that things

19:22.700 --> 19:24.700
aren't the way
they remember 'em either.

19:27.700 --> 19:29.700
One of our amazing
front desk managers,

19:29.767 --> 19:31.400
Miss Brooklyn.

19:31.467 --> 19:34.467
JOHN: Uh, have--
have you been, uh, affected?

19:34.533 --> 19:36.066
Yeah, actually because of him,

19:36.133 --> 19:39.000
I've realized that a lot,
I have, yeah.

19:39.066 --> 19:40.300
-Absolutely.
-JOHN: Like what?

19:40.367 --> 19:42.767
Well, like "Kit Kat."
"Febreze" blew my mind.

19:42.834 --> 19:44.166
"Froot Loops." (CHUCKLES)

19:44.233 --> 19:45.767
JOHN: Oh, so it's, like,
the spelling of things?

19:45.834 --> 19:48.033
Yeah, just the spelling,
and the way I remember it.

19:48.100 --> 19:50.133
JOHN: Do you think this
has a lot to do with memory,

19:50.200 --> 19:51.333
or is it something different?

19:51.400 --> 19:53.800
I personally think it's memory.
That's me.

19:53.867 --> 19:55.767
But I know these guys think
a little bit differently,

19:55.834 --> 19:57.200
but I think it's memory.

19:57.266 --> 19:58.834
-No, please be honest,
whatever you think.
-No, yeah. (LAUGHS)

